<HEADLINE>
<P>
JOHN CANDY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 As I was crossing the Mojave Desert, the radio report of John Candy's death 
was a bit overwhelming. I met him once, and he was a nice guy.The movie 
industry cannot afford to lose such quality comedians as the smiling Candy. 
</P>
<P>
 As the desert road became longer, I remembered the thank-you card I wrote to 
him that I never mailed. 
</P>
<P>
 I am a single father trying to raise four children. Entertainment is not an 
expense I can often afford. I often look for movies that will not offend or 
embarrass my family. I cannot recall one of his movies that ever made me 
uncomfortable about bringing my kids. He made us laugh and yet his characters 
sometimes made you think a little. 
</P>
<P>
 I never saw him use vulgarity to capture an audience. The writers, of course, 
play an important role. However, the actor can choose the script, and Candy 
always seemed to cast himself right. For those who have ever been overweight 
and tormented because of it, then he represented something else as well. The 
world needed John Candy to make us laugh and think at the same time. I guess 
God needed him more. Thanks, John! 
</P>
<P>
 JIM MADURA 
</P>
<P>
 San Bernardino 
</P>
</TEXT>
