<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: PLACENTIA YORBA LINDA; 7-YEAR PLAN UNVEILED FOR SCHOOL 
DISTRICT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIELLE A. FOUQUETTE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A seven-year spending plan for the Placentia-Yorba Linda Unified School 
District presented earlier this week includes provisions for a new elementary 
school in Yorba Linda and moving sixth-grade students to Kraemer Middle School. 
</P>
<P>
 But the plans proposed expenditures of more than $27 million, far more than 
the estimated income of about $17 million from developer fees and redevelopment 
income. District officials conceded they have no alternative funding source in 
mind, though they hope to develop some. The district budget this year is about 
$95 million. 
</P>
<P>
 "There are a whole list of different avenues we can explore," said district 
planner Mike Bailey. "But that is another step in the process. This report 
merely identifies the need." 
</P>
<P>
 Although the plan has not been approved by the district board, the top 
priority appears to be a proposal to expand Kraemer Middle School to include 
sixth-grade students. 
</P>
<P>
 Beginning with a $45,000 outlay designated for the current school year to 
design a larger commons and cafeteria area, the proposed expansion would cost a 
total of $1.3 million over the next seven school years. It would also add 
classrooms and other improvements. 
</P>
<P>
 The spending plan also includes an allotment of $40,000 in 1995-96 to identify 
possible sites for a 10-acre elementary school in the eastern part of the 
district. It would most likely be in the northeast portion of Yorba Linda. 
During the subsequent three years, the plan allocates $4 million to purchase 
property, $5.1 million to build the school and $750,000 to furnish and equip 
it. 
</P>
<P>
 While acknowledging that the price tag for the five-page list of projects 
exceeded the anticipated revenue from school-designated developer fees, 
district officials nonetheless called the proposals essential. 
</P>
<P>
 Other proposed projects include renovation and expansion of Esperanza High 
School in Anaheim, renovation of Bradford Stadium at Valencia High in Placentia 
and the addition of high-tech labs to each of the district's high schools and 
middle schools. DANIELLE A. FOUQUETTE 
</P>
</TEXT>
